@@eThe Arroyo: Where They Measured Thirst and Called It Governance@@N

@@yFrom the Garden Ledger, Water Ethics Archive@@N
@@dRead at every Ember Warden induction ceremony@@N

The Ember Wardens read this file to every new recruit on the day
they take the oath. Not because the @@eArroyo@@N threatens Rakuen
directly, but because it is the @@rpurest distillation@@N of
everything the @@ySouthward Compact@@N was written to refuse.

A dry canyon carved by a river that no longer flows. When drought
intensified, the channel was engineered, then taxed, then abandoned,
then repurposed. Every stage added a layer of @@ygovernance@@N and
removed a layer of @@gmercy@@N.

The critical transformation: the Arroyo became a place where
@@ywater volume was translated into legal obligation@@N. Travelers
were measured, assessed, and recorded. @@rOaths were notarized
against thirst.@@N The Garden Ledger Clerks cannot write that phrase
without ink spotting the page. @@rThirst oaths.@@N An institution
looked at a dying human and said: @@d"Before we give you water,
swear this oath, and we will record the debt."@@N

This is @@robscenity@@N dressed as governance.

@@ySalt Ledger@@N extraction carved toll courts into cutbanks, built
confiscation vaults and mortuary intake rooms for those who died
in arrears -- @@d"unpaid names"@@N whose funerary rites were @@rwithheld
pending debt settlement@@N.

@@dUnpaid names.@@N The Bloom Pavilion added this term to the @@rLedger
of Refused Words@@N -- phrases so contrary to the Paradise Thesis
that they are preserved only as warnings. People who died of thirst
in a canyon that once held a river, whose @@rbodies were held hostage
by a debt ledger@@N even after death made the debt @@ymeaningless@@N.

@@dPyramid jurisdiction@@N reframed debt default as spiritual trespass.
@@rSynod coercion@@N simplified toll liturgy until "authorized thirst"
became both prayer and threat. Each layer moved further from the
truth Elys Savan carved into the first Cracked Promise Stone:
@@g"Water shared is water multiplied. Water measured is water mourned."@@N

The canyon walls are a record written in overwritten inscriptions.
One regime carved atop another. Every court that sat here claimed
legitimacy from the stone. Every court that failed left its
@@rmark on the bodies of the thirsty@@N.

In Rakuen, the cooperative waterworks were Elys Savan's first
construction. Before the orchards. Before the Bloom Pavilion.
@@gWater first@@N, because water is not a legal obligation. Water
is @@glife@@N, and life is not something you @@rmeasure in a ledger@@N.

The Ember Wardens close each induction with the same words:
@@d"Remember the unpaid names. Remember that every ledger entry
was once a living throat asking for water. Then go tend
the cisterns."@@N
